subsection.p:
Now integrate the derivative through the inside:
\int_I dT \amp= \int_1^4 (2x+2)\,dx \amp= \left[x^2+2x\right]_1^4 \amp= 21.
Thus \boxed{\int_{\partial I}T=\int_I dT.}

Putting these together gives
\boxed{\int_{\partial[a,b]}f=\int_{[a,b]}df}
which means
\boxed{f(b)-f(a)=\int_a^b f'(x)\,dx.}

statement.p:
Let f be a C^1 function on an open interval containing [a,b]. Give
[a,b] the orientation from a to b. Then
\boxed{\int_{\partial[a,b]}f=\int_{[a,b]}df.}
Equivalently,
\boxed{f(b)-f(a)=\int_a^b f'(x)\,dx.}

